        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29912",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=stas",
                        "name": "stas",
                        "displayName": "Stanislav Malyshev",
                        "active": false
                    },
                    "body": "I don't think there's something specific to AMF - if you load bad file, PHP stops execution and produces an error. There's little that can be done about it. \nHowever, in this particular case you could use autoloading and then when you run service from a.php you would not need to include b.php. Thus, only service using b.php would be broken when b.php is broken.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=stas",
                        "name": "stas",
                        "displayName": "Stanislav Malyshev",
                        "active": false
                    },
                    "created": "2009-04-03T15:26:21.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-04-03T15:26:21.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29994",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gauravp",
                        "name": "gauravp",
                        "displayName": "Gaurav Priyadarshi",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "The problem is in cases where the files are located in separate directories, say, 'dir1\/a.php' and 'dir2\/b.php'\nNow to expose these services we will have to write a code which will include $server->setClass('a') & $server->setClass('b').\nIf we use __autoload function, firstly how will we resolve the complete path to the php files and secondly, it will still result in errors as soon as we call setClass()\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gauravp",
                        "name": "gauravp",
                        "displayName": "Gaurav Priyadarshi",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-04-06T06:14:11.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-04-06T06:14:11.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/30117",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=stas",
                        "name": "stas",
                        "displayName": "Stanislav Malyshev",
                        "active": false
                    },
                    "body": "I'm not sure I understand - could you provide complete code example (maybe by mail to stas@zend.com) that describes what problems you get with autoloading? ",
